p, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Torbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:","from the Anglo-Norman and Middle English personal name <i>T(h)urbert</i>, <i>T(h)orbert</i>, a hybrid of Old Norse <i>Thorr</i> ‘Thor’, the name of the god of thunder, + ancient Germanic <i>-berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was probably formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."],"variants":[{"name":"Turberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."]},{"name":"Turbett","meanings":["English (Warwickshire; of Norman origin): variant of   Torbet  ."]},{"name":"Torbett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Torbet   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Torbert","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Torbet  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Tarbet","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from one or more places called with Gaelic <i>tairbeart</i> ‘narrow isthmus, portage’, such as Tarbat (Ross and Cromarty).","English (Lancashire): variant of   Torbet  ."]}]},{"name":"Joana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joannah","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":23,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":32,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joana de Torbet was born in 1192, in Moreton Corbet, Shropshire, England, her father, Bartholomew de Toret, was 23 and her mother, Agnes, was 28. She had at least 1 daughter with Boulet de Booley. She died on 30 March 1236, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1192–30 March 1236":"1192–30. märts 1236","1192–1236":"1192–1236","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1192–1235":"1192–1235","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1169–1235":"1169–1235","1165–1235":"1165–1235","30 March 1236":"30. märts 1236","1165":"1165","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","1192":"1192","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","Moreton Toret,,Shropshire,England":"Moreton by Oswestry, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Moreton Corbet, Shropshire, England":"Moreton Corbet, Shropshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1192–30 March 1236":"1192–30. maaliskuuta 1236","1192–1236":"1192–1236","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1192–1235":"1192–1235","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1169–1235":"1169–1235","1165–1235":"1165–1235","30 March 1236":"30. maaliskuuta 1236","1165":"1165","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","1192":"1192","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","Moreton Toret,,Shropshire,England":"Moreton by Oswestry, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Moreton Corbet, Shropshire, England":"Moreton Corbet, Shropshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, E